sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I761006
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Glucose and cinr+cinl controlled mouse insulin degradation enzyme generator
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This generator is under control of extracellular glucose concentration and insulin activation state. High extracellular glucose concentration will turn off the generator by the binding of phosphorylated OmpR. Unless BBa_I761007 has respond to prior high extracellular glucose concentration, this generator will not turn on. This is achieved by the control of cinr and cinl. After mouse insulin degradation enzyme is generated, it will be exported and can degrade extracellular insulin.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: 2007 NYMU_Taiwan iGEM Team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This generator will turn on if and only if the extracellular glucose concentration is low and BBa_I761007 has been turned on at least once. The basic concept is that when extracellular glucose concentration is low, OmpR dephosphrylated and dissociate from its binding site. When this occurs, BBa_I761007 turns off, but the inhibitory effect of phosphorylated OmpR on this generator is relieved. While the mRNA synthesis of cinr and cinl has turned off, there are still some active CinR and CinL presented in E. coli as protein. Therefore, the generator will turn on due to the activation of the promotor BBa_R0078. Hence our goal is achieved.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: OmpR_BS
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: OmpR binding site. When position behind a promotor, it will turns that promotor into a OmpR controlled promotor. OmpR will function as an inhibitor of that promotor.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: 2007 NYMU_Taiwan iGEM Team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: This part was derived from BBa_R0082 by PCR.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I761004
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Twin arginin signal peptide is an efficient protein export signal sequence of E. coli. The purpose of this construct is to allow E. coli export mouse insulin degradation enzyme(IDE) automatically, allowing controlled insulin degradation of extracellular insulin.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: 2007 NYMU_Taiwan iGEM Team
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: NCBI accession number: BC041675 K12 E. coli genomic DNA
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: To combine TAT signal and mouse IDE, we used two separate PCR reaction to amplify each DNA fragment. We design the reverse primer of TAT signal and the forward primer of mouse IDE to be complement to each other, so when we mixed the product of each PCR reaction together, than used the forward primer of TAT signal and the reverse primer of mouse IDE to conduct PCR reaction, we can isolate the combine DNA product of TAT signal and mouse IDE. (Method devised by Dr. Chang)
